	affiliations = {Department of Immersive Convergence Content, Kwangwoon University, 20, Gwangun-ro, Nowon-gu, Seoul, 01897, South Korea; Institute of Smart City and Management, UEH University, Ho Chi Minh, 72400, Viet Nam; Immersive Content Display Center, Kwangwoon University, Seoul, 01897, South Korea; Ingenium College, Kwangwoon University, 20, Gwangun-ro, Nowon-gu, Seoul, 01897, South Korea},
	abstract = {Several studies have explored the use of hologram technology in architecture and urban design, demonstrating its feasibility. Holograms can represent 3D spatial data and offer an immersive experience, potentially replacing traditional methods such as physical 3D and offering a promising alternative to mixed-reality display technologies. Holograms can visualize realistic scenes such as buildings, cityscapes, and landscapes using the novel view synthesis technique. This study examines the suitability of spatial data collected through the Gaussian splatting method for tabletop hologram visualization. Recent advancements in Gaussian splatting algorithms allow for real-time spatial data collection of a higher quality compared to photogrammetry and neural radiance fields. Both hologram visualization and Gaussian splatting share similarities in that they recreate 3D scenes without the need for mesh reconstruction. In this research, unmanned aerial vehicle-acquired primary image data were processed for 3D reconstruction using Gaussian splatting techniques and subsequently visualized through holographic displays. Two experimental environments were used, namely, a building and a university campus. As a result, 3D Gaussian data have proven to be an ideal spatial data source for hologram visualization, offering new possibilities for real-time motion holograms of real environments and digital twins. © 2024 by the authors.},
